{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17517410","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17517410"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:52:57+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:52:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12795"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12795","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12795"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.31,0.36,0.17,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5236"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"39739"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5236","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5236"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12795"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"24214"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"1617"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4984"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8907"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9520"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44383"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"39739","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/39739"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old man who recently returned from Brazil presents with a painless, non-pruritic rash that has been progressively getting worse over the past month. He also feels generally unwell, with weight loss and intermittent fever over the same duration as rash. He reports having a cat and a dog as pet at home and having multiple sexual partners in the past. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, his temperature is 37.4\u00b0C, blood pressure 125/86 mmHg, pulse 99/min, respiratory rate 15/min. Chest and abdominal examinations are normal. He has several purple, raised, and irregularly shaped lesions on his face, neck, arms, and legs (Image). The lesions are non-tender but bleed easily when scraped or bumped. Biopsy of one of these lesions shows spindle cell vascular proliferation in the dermis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely causative organism of this condition?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Epstein Barr virus","Human T-cell lymphotropic virus-1","Human herpesvirus 8","Bartonella henselae","Leishmania"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe symptoms and rash described in the scenario are consistent with Kaposi sarcoma, a type of cancer caused by\u003Cstrong\u003E Human herpesvirus 8 (HHV-8) \u003C/strong\u003Einfection. Kaposi sarcoma is characterised by purple, raised, and irregularly shaped lesions that can occur anywhere on the body, including the face, neck, arms, and legs. The lesions are usually painless but can bleed easily.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt is the most common neoplasm in people with AIDS and other immunocompromised states. HHV-8 is a herpesvirus that is transmitted through sexual contact, blood transfusion, and organ transplantation. The patient\u0027s history of multiple sexual partners suggests that he may be at risk for HHV-8 infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEpstein Barr virus (EBV)\u003C/strong\u003E is a member of the herpes virus family and is one of the most common human viruses. It is found all over the world and spreads most commonly through bodily fluids, primarily saliva, it is most commonly associated with infectious mononucleosis. However, EBV has also been linked to malignant diseases, including Burkitt lymphoma, Hodgkin\u0027s lymphoma, hemophagocytic lymphohistiocytosis, gastric cancer, and nasopharyngeal carcinoma. However, the symptoms and clinical findings described in the scenario do not align with EBV-related cancers.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHuman T-cell lymphotropic virus-1 (HTLV-1)\u003C/strong\u003E is a retrovirus that can cause adult T-cell leukemia/lymphoma, but it is not associated with Kaposi sarcoma. Unlike Kaposi sarcoma, HTLV-1 is not typically associated with the development of skin lesions or tumours making it a less likely choice.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBartonella\u003C/strong\u003E \u003Cstrong\u003Ehenselae\u003C/strong\u003E is a bacterium that can cause cat scratch disease, which typically presents with fever and lymphadenopathy. However, it is not associated with Kaposi sarcoma. The symptoms and clinical findings described in the scenario are not consistent with cat scratch disease. Symptoms typically include a non-painful bump or blister at the site of injury and painful and swollen lymph nodes. People may feel tired, have a headache, or a fever.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELeishmania\u003C/strong\u003E is a protozoan parasite that can cause leishmaniasis, which typically presents with skin ulcers. The parasite is transmitted by the sandfly and is a very rare occurrence in Australia. The symptoms depend on the type of leishmania. Cutaneous leishmaniasis presents with an open sore at the bite site which heals leaving a scar. Mucocutaneous leishmaniasis presents with ulcers of the skin and mucosal ulcers which mainly damage the mouth and nose. Visceral leishmaniasis starts with an ulcer of skin followed by fever, low red blood cells, enlarged liver and spleen\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Csup\u003E. \u003C/sup\u003E\u003C/strong\u003EThe symptoms and clinical findings described in the scenario are not consistent with leishmaniasis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Kaposi sarcoma is caused by Human herpesvirus 8."],"references":["Bishop BN, Lynch DT. Kaposi Sarcoma. [Updated 2022 Jun 11]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2023 Jan."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"24214"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12795"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19821"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19821","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19821"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/4c91d98c-9772-40fe-bd48-c2c380104424.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/4c91d98c-9772-40fe-bd48-c2c380104424.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1316,"height":486}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"24214","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/24214"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2023-10-06T08:56:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-10T08:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5236"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"39739"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"1617","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/1617"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Herpes simplex virus type 2","synonyms":["HSV-2","HSV type 2 infection","HSV 2","Herpes simplex virus 2"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2022-04-13T19:47:52+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-20T08:50:39+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"2"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4